# Who did you work for before Clearleft? (If an agency, please include major clients)\
\
Before coming to Clearleft I was a freelance web designer. As a freelancer I worked on every part of the website, from conception, through design and development. I was particularly interested in usability and would often partake in user testing in order to improve designs.\
\
\
# What do you at Clearleft? (Not just job title, 2-3 sentences of what your job entails)\
\
I work collaboratively with visual and UX designers to transition a design into CSS, HTML and javascript. Using best practices I always aim for maintainable code which is backwards compatible and adheres to progressive enhancement, meaning that sites can take advantage of new features without giving a poor experience in older browsers. I also work with back end developers, helping them take our modular patterns of code and implement them into their environments.\
\
I'm also responsible for adding new functionality to Fontdeck, a service that provides web fonts for designers. Along with this I respond to customer support for Fontdeck, which gives me a unique insight into which features and improvements would improve the service for users.\
\
\
# What unique skills do you have within Clearleft? (ie. what are you particularly good at or interested in? eg. responsive design, user research, global experience languages)\
\
I thoroughly enjoy problem solving, and love working on responsive sites as they offer me a sense of reward upon creating a great cross platform experience. I've been described as a developer with UX sensibilities. I care deeply about the user experience for any project I work on, and want to ensure that I always meet the goals set by UX designers.\
\
Since being involved in the Fontdeck project, my enthusiasm and appreciation for Typography has become stronger. I enjoy setting tone and hierarchy in any project through the presentation of text.\
